#week-title("One", "Paul Foster Case: Methods of Study at the Adept Level")

=== Core Teaching

Paul Foster Case, in Chapter 26 of *The Tarot*, describes three ascending
levels of engagement with the Tarot that map directly onto the three years of
this curriculum.

The *first level* is intellectual study: learning the correspondences, the
Hebrew letters, the planetary and elemental attributions, the keywords. This
is the work of Year One Month 4 and Month 8.

The *second level* is imaginative contemplation: sitting with a card, looking
at it, allowing its imagery to speak at a level below ordinary analytical
thinking. This is the pathwork introduced in Year One Month 8 and deepened
across Year Two.

The *third level*, which Case calls the highest and which he insists cannot
be shortcut, is a sustained, silent concentration that approaches meditation
in the strict sense: the card is held in the mind's eye with the eyes closed,
its imagery reproduced from within rather than observed from without, and the
practitioner's awareness allowed to enter the symbolic space of the card and
move through it.

At the Adept level, the third level is the appropriate mode of engagement.
This is not a different practice from what has been building across three
years — it is the maturation of the same practice. The student who has
maintained a daily sitting and a Tarot journal across two and a half years
should now find that the cards have become genuinely interior — that the
imagery arises naturally from within rather than requiring the physical card
for stimulus.

*Case on the World card.* Key 21 — The World — Case describes as the
"perfect, self-conscious expression of the Life-Power." At the Adept level,
the World card is not a symbol of completion as a future event: it is a symbol
of what the practitioner is already, in principle, participating in. The
wreath enclosing the dancer is the completed Great Work. The dancer is not
trapped within it — she is its articulate expression.

=== Topics This Week

- Case's three levels of Tarot study: intellectual, contemplative, and meditative
- The third level as the Adept's appropriate mode
- The World card at the Adept level: completion as participation, not destination
- Reviewing how the Tarot practice has evolved across three years

#inner-work[
  *The Interior Card*

  Choose one Major Arcana card that has been especially significant across the
  three years of study. Sit for twenty minutes with your eyes closed, and
  reproduce the card's imagery from within — without looking at the physical
  card.

  Record: what elements arose clearly? What was incomplete or different from
  the physical card? What arose that was not in the physical card at all? This
  last category is significant — it is the practitioner's own inner symbolic
  material activating around the card's central theme.
]

